"{\"uid\": \"metro.co.uk-2024-07-26-paris-olympics-2024-opening-ceremony-parade-nations-order-explained-2-21302254\", \"text\": \"The Parade of Nations for theParis2024Olympic Gamesopening ceremony has been confirmed, but how does it work and when do Great Britain enter?  The Olympics got underway in the French capital on Wednesday and continued on Thursday ahead of tonight's official opening ceremony on Friday, July 26, 2024.  The opening ceremony will have a very different look this year with the event taking place on the River Seine with a special six-kilometre parade, the first time in history it has not taken place inside a stadium.  Around 600,000 people are expected to in attendance and many are anticipating it to be the largest opening ceremony in Olympic history.  The order of countries for any opening ceremony at the Olympics is\\u00a0decided alphabetically - using the host nation's official language - although there are a few exceptions, whichMetro.co.ukhas explained below.  At Tokyo 2020, nations entered according to their namesin the Japanese language, using the written form of katakana. But what is the order for the Parade of Nations at Paris 2024 and how is it all decided? Here's everything you need to know ahead of tonight's historic event on the River Seine.  As many as 94 boats are expected to take part in the Paris Olympics opening ceremony river parade to carry an estimated amount of 6,800 athletes.  The Parade of Nations will follow a six-kilometre (3.7 mile) course of the Seine, from east to west.  Starting from Pont d'Austerlitz, it will come to a stop at the Pont d'I\\u00e9na before the opening ceremony's finale at the Trocad\\u00e9ro.  As the athletes sail, a show will unfurl around them. There will be anumber of performances- withmusicians C\\u00e9line Dion and Lady Gagaexpected to appear.  Television broadcasts will begin at 6.30pm UK time, meaning you can watch the full spectacle from home.  Paris 2024 planners wanted to make the opening ceremony more accessible to the wider public, which is why they decided to hold this one on the River Seine.  The first country to enter the Parade of Nations is alwaysGreece, due to their historical role in the origin of the Olympics.  The very first ancient Olympic Games can be traced back to Olympia, in south west Greece, in 776 BC. Greece will be followed by the Refugee Olympic Team.  Great Britain are 72nd on the list for the Parade of Nations, sandwiched in-between Ghana (71st) and Grenada (73rd).  The twoTeam GBflagbearers for Paris 2024 are diverTom Daleyand rower Helen Glover.  Helen Glover and Tom Daley will carry the British flag at the Paris 2024 Opening Ceremony! \\u00f0\\u009f\\u0087\\u00ac\\u00f0\\u009f\\u0087\\u00a7@BritishRowing|@Aquatics_GBpic.twitter.com/c4Z7VGKeh1  'I am extremely proud,' Daley said. 'Being able to be flagbearer at the opening ceremony is a dream come true.'  Glover added: I never thought I would be an Olympian! Being part of history as a flagbearer, I have not really got my head round it yet. Everyone I have told so far has cried, and I cried when I was told, which goes to show how much of an honour it is and how much it means.'  France, this year's host nation, will enter last as the 205th country on the list, as per tradition.  The United States and Australia will come in as the 203rd and 204th nations, because they are hosting the next two Summer Olympics in 2028 and 2032.  Los Angeles is the host city for the next Games while the first Olympics of the 2030s will take place in Brisbane.  ArrowMORE:British Olympic chief slams decision to allow Dutch rapist to compete  ArrowMORE:Team GB hire their own chefs after being served raw meat in Olympic Village  ArrowMORE:Trains filled with Olympic athletes stopped after coordinated arson attacks  Punchy analysis, transfer talk and more from Metro's football experts, sent straight to your inbox every week.  Let us know which team you support.Close  This site is protected by reCAPTCHA and theGoogle Privacy PolicyandTerms of Serviceapply. Your information will be used in line with ourPrivacy Policy  Punchy analysis, transfer talk and more from Metro's football experts, sent straight to your inbox every week.  Let us know which team you support.Close  This site is protected by reCAPTCHA and theGoogle Privacy PolicyandTerms of Serviceapply. Your information will be used in line with ourPrivacy Policy\"}"